        <marginalia anchor_text="Placet creari dece[m]uiros" hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Xviri: Rerum domini. etiam sine prouocatione. Vnde Oligarchia. quantò maior, tantò minor.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Decemviri: rulers of affairs, even without right of appeal. From which Oligarchy. The greater [the institution], the smaller [the power].
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Altera Status Romani Innouatio. Nec Reges, nec Consules, nec Decemuiri, nec vlli magistratus placent diu, vbi necessitas summi, fixiq[ue] 
                        Imperij non imponitur; sed penès populum est potestas mutandi. Quem Romanus poeta prudenter, iusteq[ue] vocauit Belluam multorum capitum. 
                        Neq[ue] enim vllus vsus talium magistratuum in fixo Regno: et leui pollice pra[e]teriri possunt, qua[e] sunt nimiùm popularia, aut Oligarchica: 
                        nisi quatenùs iuuat obitèr notare rationem dissimilium formarum Gubernandi: et tantò solidiore iudicio adha[e]rescere optimis, aut necessarijs.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <X-ref book_title="Epistles" language="LA" person="Horace" text="belluam multorum capitum"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Another innovation of the Roman state. Neither Kings, nor Consuls, nor Decemviri, nor any other magistrates satisfy for long, when supreme, 
                unchangeable authority is not imposed as a necessary requirement, but when the people has the power to change. And a Roman poet sagaciously 
                and rightly called them "a monster with many heads". For there is no use whatsoever for such magistrates in an unchangeable rule and we can pass over 
                ‘with nimble thumb’ the elements that are too popularist, or the oligarchical, except that it is helpful to a certain extent to note in passing the reason for disparate forms of government, 
                and with all the more solid judgement stick to the best or necessary ones.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
